World Happiness

Abigail Protin and Daniela Lulli

Introduction

The World Happiness Report is a survey of the state of global happiness that ranks countries by how happy their citizens perceive themselves to be. We investigated what factors may correlate to the estimated happiness scores of each country. In this tutorial, we will walk through how we obtained and organized our data and how we determined which factors were most significant in predicting the happiness scores. From there, we create a linear regression model to predict the happiness score of countries given the predictors. Once our model was created, we tested it and made sure that our test results were accurate. We then used data visualization tools to display happiness scores and predictors around the globe.

Libraries Required

In [130]:
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns                                # for violin plot and for regplot 
import statsmodels.api as sm                         # for linear regression model
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split # split data
from scipy import stats                              # for pearsonr value of interaction terms
import folium                                        # for interactive map

Obtaining the Data

We obtained our data from Knoema. It is a site that maintains a comprehensive global dataset. This dataset contains statistics for many countries regarding topics in Agriculture, Economy, Health, and many others. For our purposes, we chose to look at the following factors:

  1. Food Production
  2. Female Obesity (% of the population)
  3. Male Obesity (% of the population)
  4. Life Expectancy (in years)
  5. Education Expenditure per Capita (in US dollars)
  6. Health Expenditure per Captia (in US dollars) We used these factors to determine the happiness score of the country, which was also given in the Knoema dataset. The Happiness Scores were caluclated through a survey asking people to rank their happiness on a scale from 0 to 10.

We downloaded the data for each factor as csv files, read them in, and combined them into one pandas dataframe joining by Country and Year. This is shown below.

In [106]:
df = pd.read_csv('Food Production.csv')
obese_female = pd.read_csv('Obesity Female.csv')
obese_male = pd.read_csv('Obesity Male.csv')
life_exp = pd.read_csv('Life Expectancy.csv')
ed_exp = pd.read_csv('Education Expenditure.csv')
health_exp = pd.read_csv('Health Expenditure.csv')
happiness = pd.read_csv('Happiness Score.csv')

frames = [obese_female, obese_male,
         life_exp, ed_exp, health_exp, happiness]
for f in frames: 
    df = pd.merge(df, f, on = ['Country', 'Year'], how = 'outer')
df.head()

Tidying the Data

Before analyzing the data, we drop all rows with null values. To predict the happiness score, numerical values were required for all factors, so rows with missing data are useless.

Exploring the Data

We first made a violin plot of the happiness scores from each year to get an idea of the basic distribution of the scores.

In [71]:
ax = sns.violinplot(x='Year', y='Happiness Score', data=df)

Next, we ran a linear regression model on all of our independent variables with the dependent variable being the Happiness Score. We displayed the summary to get the pvalues for each factor to determine if they were relevant to our model.

In [118]:
x = df[['Food Production Index','Obesity Female', 'Obesity Male',
                 'Life expectancy', 'Education Expenditure', 'Health Expenditure']]
y = df[['Happiness Score']]
model = sm.OLS(y, x).fit()
model.summary()

As you can, the majority of the resulting pvalues are below 0.05, which is what we decided to use as our threshold for whether a factor was significant or not. The Food Production Index, however, has an extremely high p value, so we will drop that from our model.

The last thing we need to do before creating our model is see if any of the predictors are related to each other, in which case we would need to add an interaction term to our model. To check this, we plot each combination of predictors against each other with a regression line and compute the pearson r squared value. We wrote a function to quickly do both of these things, called 'interaction'.

In [119]:
def interaction(x, y):
    print(stats.pearsonr(df[x], df[y])[0] ** 2)
    ax1 = sns.regplot(x=x, y=y, data=df)

We decided that our 'threshold' for whether two variables were correlated was an r squared value of 0.5 or above, which was true for male and female obesity and male obesity and life expectancy. Now, we will create interaction terms for these by multiplying the related factors together. We added these interaction terms to our dataframe.

In [125]:
df['int_obesity'] = df['Obesity Male']*df['Obesity Female']
df['int_life'] = df['Obesity Male']*df['Life expectancy']
df.head()

Now we're ready to make our model!

First, we have to split our data into a train and a test set in order to avoid overfitting our model.

In [126]:
train, test = train_test_split(df, train_size=0.75, random_state=40)
xtrain = train[['Obesity Female', 'Obesity Male',
                 'Life expectancy', 'Education Expenditure', 'Health Expenditure','int_obesity']]
ytrain = train[['Happiness Score']]
# qualityTrain = pd.DataFrame(train, columns=df.columns)
# qualityTest = pd.DataFrame(test, columns=df.columns)

Now we are ready to train our model using the Ordinary Least Squares method, commonly known as linear regression. We will get the r squared value of this model to determine how good it is.

In [127]:
model = sm.OLS(ytrain, xtrain).fit()
model.rsquared
Out[127]:
0.991370876357963

Our r squared value is very close to 1, which indicates that the model is very good.

Testing our model

We will now use the model on the test data, and compare the model's predictions with the actual happiness scores. We will compare by plotting the expected against the actual. A good model would show a strong linear trend.

In [128]:
xtest = test[['Obesity Female', 'Obesity Male',
                 'Life expectancy', 'Education Expenditure', 'Health Expenditure','int_obesity']]
ytest = test[['Happiness Score']]
predicted = model.predict(xtest)
ax1 = sns.regplot(x=predicted, y=ytest, data=df)

The scatter plot above shows a clear linear trend. While it's not perfect, it is accurate for the majority of the data indicating that our model works well in predicting happiness scores.

Data Visualization

To get an idea of what happiness looks like around the world, we use the folium module to create an interactive map that displays happiness scores as a color gradient.

In [141]:
url = 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/python-visualization/folium/master/examples/data'
country_shapes = f'{url}/world-countries.json'

m = folium.Map(location=[45.9432, 24.9668], zoom_start=4)
folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=country_shapes,
    name='World Happiness',
    data=df,
    columns=['Country', 'Happiness Score'],
    key_on='feature.properties.name',
    fill_color='PuRd',
    nan_fill_color='white'
).add_to(m)
m
Out[141]:
Make this Notebook Trusted to load map: File -> Trust Notebook

The darker pink colors have higher happiness scores compared to lighter pink countries, which have lower scores. We did not have enough data on the white countries to compute their happiness score.

Real-World Application

Everyone wants to be happy. There are many studies that show things individual people can do to increase their happiness. Our tutorial finds what factors outside of our individual control affect the overall happiness of our communities as a whole. Our results show that life expectancy, obesity, health care, and education may have an impact on one's happiness. If countries allocated more resources toward improving those four aspects, it is likely that people around the world would be happier!
